<P>Strange though he were all beauty yet they &s;hould &s;ee him, and yet &s;ee no beauty. That is, they &s;hall &s;ee him, and yet no<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;ee him. They &s;ee not wood for trees. What is thy beloved more than other beloveds? What is Chri&s;t more than an ordinary man? What is the Go&s;|pel more than an ordinary Story? What is the Spirit? What is Truth? What is there in this Faith and Love, in this Ho<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">ine&s;s and Righteou&s;ne&s;s, in this Peace of Con|&s;cience, and Joy of the Holy Gho&s;t? What &s;ub&s;tance is there in them? Where is the Glory, and wherein is the Excellency of them? <HI>Which may came the Spirit of the Lord from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> to thee? <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;halt know in that day, when thou &s;ha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter">t cal to the Mountains to fall on thee, &amp; the Rocks to hide thee, from face of God &amp; the Lamb We know whom we have believed. We know that we know him We &s;peak that which we know, &amp; te&s;tifie what we have &s;een. We have an &V;nion &s;ee<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> the Holy One, we know all things God hath revealed them to us by his Spirit, for the &s;pirit &s;earcheth all things, even the deep things of God. Now we have received not the &s;pirit of this world, but the &s;pirit which is of God, that we might know the things that are freely given to us <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 word">
