of life. <NOTE N="a" PLACE="marg">2 <HI>Cor</HI> 5 4 1 <HI>Cor</HI> 15.54</NOTE> Fear not, O my children; Come, and I will &s;hew you the enemy that you dreaded. See, here lies the King of terrours, like <HI>Si&s;era</HI> in the tent, fa&s;tened to the ground, with the nail &s;truck through his temples. Behold the grateful pre&s;ent, the head of your enemy in a Charger. I bequeath you your con|quered adver&s;ary, and make over death as your Legacy. <NOTE N="y" PLACE="marg">1 <HI>Cor.</HI> 3 22.</NOTE> O death where is thy &s;ting? where now is thine armour where|in thou tru&s;ted&s;t? <NOTE N="z" PLACE="marg">1 <HI>Cor.</HI> 15.55</NOTE> Come my people, enter into your chambers: <NOTE N="a" PLACE="marg"><HI>I&s;a.</HI> 26 20</NOTE> Come to your beds of du&s;t, and lay you down in peace, and let your fle&s;h re&s;t in hope; <NOTE N="b" PLACE="marg"><HI>I&s;a.</HI> 57.2</NOTE> for even in this fle&s;h &s;hall you &s;ee God. <NOTE N="c" PLACE="marg"><HI>P&s;al.</HI> 10 91. <HI>Job</HI> 19.25, 26, 27</NOTE> O ye &s;lain of death, your carka&s;es, now as loath&s;ome as the carrion in the ditch, will I redeem from the power of the grave, <NOTE N="d" PLACE="marg"><HI>P&s;al.</HI> 49 15</NOTE> and fa&s;hion tho&s;e vile bodies like unto the glorious body of your ex|alted Redeemer. <NOTE N="e" PLACE="marg"><HI>Phil</HI> 3.21</NOTE> Look, if you can o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="pdcc" EXTENT="1 letter"> the Sun, when &s;hining in his &s;trength, with &s;uch dazling glory will I cloath you O ye of little faith <NOTE N="f" PLACE="marg"><HI>Matt.</HI> 15 43. <HI>From the Dun|geon of e|ternal darkne&s;s</HI></NOTE>.</P>
<P>From the terrible dungeon of eternal darkne&s;s do I hereby free you, Fear not, you &s;hall not be hurt of the &s;econd death, <NOTE N="g" PLACE="marg"><HI>Rev.</HI> 2.11 <HI>Rom</HI> 8.1</NOTE> you are delivered from the wrath to come, and &s;hall never come into con|demnation <NOTE N="h" PLACE="marg">1 <HI>The&s;.</HI> 1.10. <HI>Job.</HI> 5.24</NOTE>. The flames of <HI>Tophet</HI> &s;hall
